SIMPLE: snapper
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Snapper
<hw>Snap"per</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One who,
or that which, snaps; <as>as, a <ex>snapper</ex> up of trifles; the
<ex>snapper</ex> of a whip.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of several species of
large sparoid food fishes of the genus <gen>Lutjanus</gen>, abundant on
the southern coasts of the United States and on both coasts of tropical
America.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The red snapper (<spn>Lutjanus aya</spn> syn.
<spn>Lutjanus Blackfordi</spn>) and the gray, or mangrove, snapper
(<spn>Lutjanus griseus</spn>) are large and abundant species. The name
is loosely applied to various other fishes, as the bluefish, the
rosefish, the red grouper, etc. See <er>Rosefish</er>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A snapping turtle; <as>as, the
alligator <ex>snapper</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The green woodpecker, or
yaffle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>A snap beetle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Teleg.)</fld> <def>A device with a flexible metal
tongue for producing clicks like those of the sounder.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A string bean.</def> <mark>[Colloq., U.
S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Snapping</ent>⟦br⟧
